re their customers may be located.<br>
<br>
So, a company based in the middle east would be required to apply their legal rules to their customers.  If it were illegal for a woman's face to be seen in public in a computer game, then guess what, that's how the computer game would be, even for those in other countries.  In some cases they might be allowed to bend the rules to say, &quot;These rules MAY not apply to people in other countries and/or states&quot;, but then they would run into other problems, so it's easier to make a blanket rule that they apply to everyone.<br>
<br>
As for privacy, there are laws in some states in the USA that allow a home owner to shoot anyone in their home without permission(Texas and possibly others).  For computers, those who look around your computer without permission, regardless for how difficult it is are considered hackers, they are NOT allowed to look around your computer environment without your permission.  BUT, if you give them permission by downloading a given utility, you may have given permission for them to do that.  In general, most people do NOT want people to just see what they are doing on their computer.  Their e-mail should be as protected as normal mail(tampering with mail is a federal offense here in the USA).<br>
<br>
From the tech support perspective, there are some very valid reasons why they would want to see what you have running.  The Windows XP print spooler for example can cause problems, or Internet connection shareing, and so on.  You'd be amazed at how many people just don't follow instructions.  A tech support rep will say, &quot;Now, in the task list, read off to me each process running&quot;, and the person will only read off half the processes because they are running 5 web browser instances, Seti@home, downloading or uploading their e-mail, etc and don't want to admit it.  I don't agree with them randomly checking your computer, but if you call for tech support, it DOES make it easier for them to see what's going on with your computer.<br>
<br>
<br>
